From: nix-wasm <eric@codebutler.com>
Date: Thu, 19 Jun 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] wasm: collect netfs readahead inline (no kworker offload)

Fixes the full-NixOS boot deadlock in the getty/login exec chain under
per-process memory (Task 2.3). The root cause is NOT the per-process-memory
machinery itself — it is a pre-existing architectural mismatch that Task 2.3's
timing/allocation changes tipped from latent into a hard wedge.

netfs (used by the 9P `/nix` mount, cache=loose) issues page reads inline
(v9fs_issue_read -> p9_client_read is synchronous over our SAB transport) but
OFFLOADS the *collection* phase — the step that marks folios uptodate and
UNLOCKS them — to a workqueue (system_dfl_wq) when NETFS_RREQ_OFFLOAD_COLLECTION
is set, which netfs_readahead always sets. On this port the guest runs maxcpus=1
with COOPERATIVE scheduling: a worker that blocks calls schedule() and only the
idle task services device IRQs, only once every runnable task has parked. When 8
gettys exec busybox+ash from the 9P store at once, each exec's page-cache reads
spawn forced/async readahead whose collection is queued to a kworker; that
kworker is runnable but can never get the single CPU, because an exec task is
wedged holding the CPU (parked in folio_wait_bit_common for a readahead folio
that only the kworker would unlock) and the other gettys are blocked acquiring
the global nommu_region_sem. The readahead folios stay LOCKED forever ->
filemap_get_pages() -> folio_wait_bit_common() never returns -> no forward
progress. (Verified by isolation: with wasm_user_as OFF the same userspace boots
to a shell; with it ON the system wedges with 1 task in do_mmap, 1 in
down_write(nommu_region_sem), and 4 in folio_wait_bit_common <- filemap_read,
plus parked kworkers.)

Async-offload completion is fundamentally unsafe on a single cooperative CPU:
any path that parks the only running task while waiting for a kworker to make
progress can deadlock. The correct fix removes the kworker from the critical
completion path: drive netfs read collection INLINE.

netfs already supports inline collection — netfs_wait_for_in_progress() runs
netfs_collect_in_app() in the waiting thread whenever NETFS_RREQ_OFFLOAD_COLLECTION
is clear (that is exactly how the synchronous netfs_read_folio() path completes).
So under CONFIG_WASM we make netfs_readahead behave like read_folio: do NOT set
OFFLOAD_COLLECTION, and wait for the read to complete (collecting + unlocking the
folios in this thread) before returning. The reads were already synchronous over
our transport, so this only moves the folio unlock off the (unschedulable) kworker
and onto the issuing thread — no new round-trips, deterministic unlock, and the
nommu_region_sem holder always drains. Readahead becomes synchronous on this port,
the correct trade on a cooperative single CPU (the served /nix store is read-only,
so there is no writeback interaction).

Guarded by CONFIG_WASM so every other arch keeps the upstream async-offload
behavior unchanged.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 <noreply@anthropic.com>
---
--- a/fs/netfs/buffered_read.c
+++ b/fs/netfs/buffered_read.c
@@ -348,7 +348,19 @@
 	if (IS_ERR(rreq))
 		return;
 
+#ifndef CONFIG_WASM
+	/*
+	 * wasm (maxcpus=1, cooperative scheduling): do NOT offload the netfs
+	 * read collection phase to a workqueue. Offloaded collection (mark folio
+	 * uptodate + UNLOCK) depends on a kworker being scheduled, which deadlocks
+	 * when the single CPU is held by a task parked in folio_wait_bit_common()
+	 * waiting for those very folios to be unlocked. Without this flag the read
+	 * is collected INLINE by the waiter (netfs_collect_in_app), exactly like the
+	 * synchronous read_folio path — see netfs_wait_for_in_progress() and the
+	 * netfs_wait_for_read() call added at the end of this function.
+	 */
 	__set_bit(NETFS_RREQ_OFFLOAD_COLLECTION, &rreq->flags);
+#endif
 
 	ret = netfs_begin_cache_read(rreq, ictx);
 	if (ret == -ENOMEM || ret == -EINTR || ret == -ERESTARTSYS)
@@ -365,6 +377,16 @@
 		goto cleanup_free;
 	netfs_read_to_pagecache(rreq, ractl);
 
+#ifdef CONFIG_WASM
+	/*
+	 * Drive collection in THIS thread (folios get unlocked here, not by a
+	 * kworker) so a cooperative single CPU never wedges. The 9P reads were
+	 * already synchronous over the SAB transport, so this adds no round-trips —
+	 * it only moves the folio unlock off the (unschedulable) kworker.
+	 */
+	netfs_wait_for_read(rreq);
+#endif
+
 	return netfs_put_request(rreq, netfs_rreq_trace_put_return);
 
 cleanup_free:
